  • Misappropriate ID Info - Obtain Money [Modifiers: Repeater], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.201(2)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called for a restitution hearing.  Defendant Jennifer S Krauss in court with attorney Jennifer Flynn.  Jayne Davis Dewire appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  The court addresses the only factor which is the ability to pay.  Attorney Flynn makes statements.  Attorney DeWire makes statements.  Court makes an oral ruling:  Court epects the defendant to work more than full time to pay back the restitution.  Court orders the defendant pay a minimum of $75.00 per month commencing January 1, 2017 until April 1, 2017 when she is to commence paying $125.00 per month.  Attorney Flynn makes statements regarding early termination of probation.  Court orders that if the $111,095.00 is paid early, the Court will allow early termination of probation after 5 years.  Judgment of conviction to be amended.
